      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Jack Alan Robbins is the editor of <emph render="italic">Granville Hicks in the New masses</emph> (1974) and <emph render="italic">James T. Farrell: Literary Essays 1954-74</emph> (1976), among other works.</p><p>Granville Hicks (1901-1982) was an American Marxist and later anti-Marxist novelist, literary critic, educator, and editor.</p><p>Maurice Merleau-Ponty (1908-1961) was a French philosopher who  wrote on perception, art, and politics.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Jack Robbins Manuscript</emph> consists of a typescript manuscript of Robbins' book, <emph render="italic">Marxism and the Humanist Perspective</emph>.   An included note from the author indicates that some portion of the book deals with American author Granville Hicks.  There are also a few pages of reader responses and a letter from University Press of America, to whom Robbins had submitted the manuscript.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
